      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walk Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 3-minute brisk walk to warm up the foot and get blood flowing before any running. This is non-negotiable for plantar fasciitis management.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a fully conversational easy pace — 5:58/km or slower. If you feel any foot discomfort at any point, immediately drop to a walk. There is no shame in walking; it is part of the plan.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish with a 3-minute easy walk. Gently stretch your calves and plantar fascia after — heel drops off a step if pain-free, or seated towel stretches.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute brisk walk before any running. Loosen up the ankles with gentle circles. Check in with your foot — any sharp pain means today is a walk-only day, and that is a completely valid outcome.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3-minute walk to bring heart rate down. Calf stretches and plantar fascia massage with a frozen water bottle if available. Ice the foot for 10–15 minutes if any soreness is present.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, this is your first run of the week and the goal is simple: finish feeling the same or better than when you started. Your recent runs at 5:58/km with no foot pain are genuinely encouraging — that consistency over the past few weeks is exactly the foundation we are building on. The 20-minute cap is your physiotherapist's guidance and we are honouring it fully. No speed work, no extra distance. Think of this run as a check-in with your body, not a performance. Your VDOT of 46.5 from your pre-injury 10K tells us your aerobic engine is strong — right now we are just carefully rebuilding the load tolerance in your foot so that engine has a healthy chassis to run on.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Foot Check\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk warmup. Pay close attention to how the foot feels first thing — morning stiffness is common with plantar fasciitis. If stiffness is present, extend the walk warmup by 2–3 minutes before transitioning to running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational running at 5:58/km. Use a run/walk approach if needed — for example, 4 minutes running, 1 minute walking — especially if Monday's run left any residual soreness. Listen to your foot, not your ego.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk cooldown. Foot care routine: calf stretches, plantar fascia stretch, and ice if any soreness.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes minimum. If the foot felt sore after Monday's run, consider making today a 20-minute walk instead — that still counts as active recovery and keeps the plan on track.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk cooldown, then your full foot care routine. Note any changes in how the foot felt compared to Monday — this information is valuable for your physiotherapist and for adjusting the plan.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek run serves two purposes: maintaining the aerobic stimulus and gathering information about how your foot is responding to the increased frequency. Two runs in a week is already a meaningful step forward from where you were in early March. The easy pace at 5:58/km keeps you well within the aerobic zone — your easy pace range goes up to 5:58/km based on your VDOT, so this is the conservative end of that range, which is exactly right for a return-to-run phase. If you need to run/walk today, that is not a step backward — it is smart load management.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Long Run — Easy and Exploratory\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk warmup for 3 minutes. Saturday runs often feel different to weekday runs — take your time here. Check in with the foot before committing to running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running at 5:58/km or slower. This is your longest effort of the week in terms of intent, though the duration matches your other runs for now. Focus on relaxed form — soft footfall, slight forward lean, arms low and relaxed. If the foot speaks up, walk immediately.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk cooldown. This is a good day for a slightly longer post-run foot care routine — calf stretches, plantar fascia work, and ice. You have the weekend to recover before Monday.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute walk. Saturday is your designated long run day and even though the duration is capped at 20 minutes right now, treating it with the same ritual as a long run — proper warmup, mindful pacing, thorough cooldown — builds good habits for when the distance grows.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Thorough cooldown walk and foot care. Consider a gentle calf raise routine (pain-free range only) as part of your post-run routine — eccentric calf loading is often recommended for plantar fasciitis management, but confirm this with your physiotherapist first.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your Saturday long run, and right now 'long' simply means the third run of the week — and that is a real achievement given where you were in early March with just one run per week. Three runs in a week at consistent easy effort is meaningful aerobic work. The 10% weekly volume progression rule means we are being deliberate about not rushing this. Your total weekly volume this week sits around 11–12 km across three runs, which is a modest but appropriate step up from your recent history. The goal of this entire week is to finish Sunday feeling like you could have done more — that feeling is the signal that the plan is working. No speed work, no tempo, no intervals — your physiotherapist's clearance is the gate, and we respect that completely. When you do get cleared for more, your aerobic base will be ready.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
